WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:02.440
I'm not the first person at this conference

00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:03.680
to talk about renv.

00:00:03.680 --> 00:00:07.560
In 2020, Kevin Ushay introduced the renv package.

00:00:07.560 --> 00:00:10.760
And in 2022, David Aja gave the talk,

00:00:10.760 --> 00:00:12.840
You Should Use Renv.

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:15.760
So where are we at today in 2025?

00:00:15.760 --> 00:00:18.799
Here's some posts I've pulled from social media.

00:00:18.799 --> 00:00:21.559
Andrew says he's about to resubmit an R&R,

00:00:21.559 --> 00:00:23.520
which means it's time for the obligatory fight

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:24.980
with updating renv.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:28.040
TJ says, the restore on renv

00:00:28.040 --> 00:00:31.000
never works on the first few goes either.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.560
And Libby says, I have a tolerate-hate relationship

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:37.680
with renv, which is unfortunate

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:40.500
because renv is a wonderful package.

00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:46.380
And Kevin and David are both fantastic software engineers,

00:00:46.380 --> 00:00:48.480
but sometimes there's a divide

00:00:48.480 --> 00:00:51.240
between software engineers and data scientists

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:53.340
such that they cannot anticipate

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:55.840
all of the truly weird and wonderful ways

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:57.259
we try to use their package.

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:01.919
So this talk is for frustrated renv users

00:01:01.919 --> 00:01:04.099
and potential renv users.

00:01:04.099 --> 00:01:05.379
If you're in the potential bucket,

00:01:05.379 --> 00:01:07.440
I'm gonna do my best to get you up to speed,

00:01:07.440 --> 00:01:09.839
but I might go a little fast for you.

00:01:09.839 --> 00:01:11.680
And for the frustrated renv user,

00:01:11.680 --> 00:01:14.639
it's because you've had an experience like this,

00:01:14.639 --> 00:01:17.199
where you attempt to renv restore,

00:01:17.199 --> 00:01:20.839
you download 19 packages in 25 seconds,

00:01:20.839 --> 00:01:24.879
and after all of that time waiting, you have a failure.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:27.400
And at this point, you're trying things again

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:29.239
in a different order, and you feel like

00:01:29.239 --> 00:01:31.000
you're banging against a copy machine

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:32.699
hoping for a different outcome.

00:01:34.099 --> 00:01:35.519
And I think the problem is,

00:01:35.519 --> 00:01:39.059
when users open a project backed by renv,

00:01:39.059 --> 00:01:41.959
they feel like they have one button they can push,

00:01:41.959 --> 00:01:44.199
and that's renv restore.

00:01:44.199 --> 00:01:45.360
So I hope to convince you

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:47.760
you have a second button you can push,

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:49.760
which is evaluate your project state

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:51.860
against your current R configuration.

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:54.839
Even if you do that, I'm not promising

00:01:54.839 --> 00:01:56.620
it's going to be smooth sailing.

00:01:56.620 --> 00:01:59.059
This is me preparing for this talk.

00:01:59.059 --> 00:02:00.379
I submitted the talk title,

00:02:00.379 --> 00:02:02.019
How to Make Renv Actually Work,

00:02:02.019 --> 00:02:04.419
and I downgraded it to Practical Renv.

00:02:04.419 --> 00:02:09.419
So my goal is to empower renv users

00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:14.259
to successfully restore a project environment

00:02:14.259 --> 00:02:18.460
by either diagnosing or avoiding restore errors.

00:02:18.460 --> 00:02:21.020
To do that, we need a shared baseline understanding

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:23.220
with an intro to renv.

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:24.820
We're also going to need to get into the weeds

00:02:24.820 --> 00:02:26.220
of package installation,

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:28.860
because that is what restore does for you.

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:30.940
And then we're going to get into a concrete example

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:32.419
with projects over time.

00:02:33.500 --> 00:02:34.539
So let's get started.

00:02:35.979 --> 00:02:38.259
This is from the first sentence of the website.

00:02:38.259 --> 00:02:42.100
The rrenv package helps you create reproducible environments

00:02:42.100 --> 00:02:44.059
for your R projects.

00:02:44.059 --> 00:02:46.880
So let's break down this important word, reproducible.

00:02:48.059 --> 00:02:50.460
There's a spectrum of reproducibility.

00:02:50.460 --> 00:02:53.759
On the lowest end of the spectrum, we have code,

00:02:53.759 --> 00:02:56.279
and the middle ground, we have code

00:02:56.279 --> 00:03:00.360
and associated package versions at the time of execution.

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:02.800
And on the highest order of reproducibility,

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:06.399
we have code, package versions, R version,

00:03:06.399 --> 00:03:09.559
your system dependencies, and your operating system.

00:03:09.559 --> 00:03:12.539
And where rrenv fits is in the middle,

00:03:12.539 --> 00:03:15.000
with code and package versions,

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:18.199
which is both the beauty and the challenge of rrenv.

00:03:18.199 --> 00:03:20.880
The beauty being that it doesn't have all of the overhead

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:22.399
of the upper end of the spectrum,

00:03:22.399 --> 00:03:25.199
and the challenge being that it doesn't address

00:03:25.199 --> 00:03:27.860
the overhead of the upper end of the spectrum.

00:03:29.679 --> 00:03:33.119
We also need to talk about this really important word helps.

00:03:33.119 --> 00:03:35.119
The rrenv package helps you

00:03:35.119 --> 00:03:37.119
create reproducible environments.

00:03:37.119 --> 00:03:39.960
It does not do it for you.

00:03:39.960 --> 00:03:41.440
When you use rrenv,

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:44.839
there is an immense amount of user responsibility.

00:03:46.199 --> 00:03:47.720
So here's an example project.

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:49.679
I'm going to call it jsonlite-example,

00:03:49.679 --> 00:03:53.119
and I initialized it in February of this year.

00:03:53.119 --> 00:03:56.479
At this point, rrenv is not activated on this project.

00:03:56.479 --> 00:03:58.119
I have an rproj file,

00:03:58.119 --> 00:04:00.880
and I have a single file called script.r,

00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.320
which has one line on it, library jsonlite.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:07.199
I can initialize rrenv with rrenv init,

00:04:07.199 --> 00:04:08.440
in which case I get the message

00:04:08.440 --> 00:04:10.179
that I'm recording versions of R

00:04:10.179 --> 00:04:12.119
and packages in my lock file,

00:04:12.119 --> 00:04:13.479
and in my project directory,

00:04:13.479 --> 00:04:15.759
I additionally get a .er profile,

00:04:15.759 --> 00:04:18.160
an rrenv lock, and an rrenv directory.

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:21.519
And then when I'm iterating on this project,

00:04:21.519 --> 00:04:24.119
I'll do some combination of installing new packages

00:04:24.119 --> 00:04:26.600
and snapshotting to record those to my lock file,

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:28.359
and this is pretty smooth sailing.

00:04:29.799 --> 00:04:33.260
And so what I have is I have this initial project,

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:35.880
and my R versions and my package versions,

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:39.119
they are all released at different points in time.

00:04:39.119 --> 00:04:42.480
They are all available for different lengths of time,

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:45.540
and I'm taking a single slice of that point in time

00:04:45.540 --> 00:04:50.299
that represents latest available versions at that date.

00:04:50.299 --> 00:04:51.899
So I have my initial project.

00:04:53.540 --> 00:04:55.899
Now let's talk about package installation.

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:00.779
A library is a directory containing installed packages.

00:05:00.779 --> 00:05:02.500
It's just a folder on your machine

00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:04.980
where those installed packages go.

00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:07.739
When I don't have rrenv activated on my project,

00:05:07.739 --> 00:05:10.619
I have two library paths available to me.

00:05:10.619 --> 00:05:13.320
One's a system path, one's a user path,

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:14.299
and I want you to notice

00:05:14.299 --> 00:05:18.140
that they're both associated with R version of 4.4,

00:05:18.140 --> 00:05:20.739
which is why when R 4.5 is released,

00:05:20.739 --> 00:05:22.619
Hadley posts on social media,

00:05:22.619 --> 00:05:25.279
happy reinstalling all your R packages day

00:05:25.279 --> 00:05:26.859
to all those who celebrate,

00:05:26.859 --> 00:05:29.500
because you will physically get a new directory

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:32.500
on your machine in which you need to install those packages.

00:05:34.100 --> 00:05:37.119
And so when I don't have rrenv activated on my project,

00:05:37.119 --> 00:05:40.059
I have a shared package environment.

00:05:40.059 --> 00:05:43.940
I have one library that all of my projects point to.

00:05:44.619 --> 00:05:46.459
That one library contains a single version

00:05:46.459 --> 00:05:48.859
of JSON Lite 1.8.9,

00:05:48.859 --> 00:05:50.859
and all of my projects are forced

00:05:50.859 --> 00:05:52.440
to use that single version.

00:05:53.619 --> 00:05:57.820
And again, this is all under the umbrella of R 4.4.

00:05:59.459 --> 00:06:02.059
When I do have rrenv activated on my project,

00:06:02.059 --> 00:06:05.320
I again have two library paths available.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:09.940
And again, these are associated with R version of 4.4.

00:06:09.940 --> 00:06:12.940
Additionally, one of these is project-specific

00:06:12.940 --> 00:06:14.700
for my JSON Lite example,

00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:17.440
and the other one points to my global cache.

00:06:18.779 --> 00:06:20.660
So when I do have rrenv activated,

00:06:20.660 --> 00:06:23.739
I have an isolated package environment.

00:06:23.739 --> 00:06:26.700
I have a global cache that contains every version

00:06:26.700 --> 00:06:28.980
of JSON Lite I could possibly want to use

00:06:28.980 --> 00:06:30.820
across all of my projects,

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:33.299
and now all of my projects can be associated

00:06:33.299 --> 00:06:35.660
with a different version of JSON Lite,

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:38.839
and this is under the umbrella of R 4.4.

00:06:39.839 --> 00:06:42.959
And when we think about any given project,

00:06:42.959 --> 00:06:44.279
they have project layers.

00:06:44.279 --> 00:06:46.320
We'll call this the project onion.

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:47.440
In our innermost layer,

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:50.160
we have our .rparge file and rrenv lock.

00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:52.119
Then we have the packages that are associated

00:06:52.119 --> 00:06:54.299
with our analysis, the R version,

00:06:54.299 --> 00:06:57.339
the system dependencies, and the operating system.

00:06:57.339 --> 00:06:59.559
So keep in mind where rrenv operates

00:06:59.559 --> 00:07:02.500
in those innermost layer touching the packages.

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:06.519
Now the rrenv lock is a JSON file

00:07:06.519 --> 00:07:07.839
that contains information

00:07:07.839 --> 00:07:10.459
from the installed packages description file.

00:07:10.459 --> 00:07:12.519
Let's walk through this a bit.

00:07:12.519 --> 00:07:14.519
It contains information about the versions

00:07:14.519 --> 00:07:17.200
of R and JSON Lite and rrenv.

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:20.040
It contains information about the repositories,

00:07:20.040 --> 00:07:21.239
which we just heard a lot about.

00:07:21.239 --> 00:07:24.160
That's where you actually installed your package from.

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:27.260
If you haven't done any configuration on your machine,

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:30.399
your default repository probably points to CRAN

00:07:30.399 --> 00:07:33.100
at the URL cloudrproject.org.

00:07:34.019 --> 00:07:36.320
There's other repositories out there

00:07:37.119 --> 00:07:38.119
that you can install packages from.

00:07:38.119 --> 00:07:39.559
And we'll be talking more about

00:07:39.559 --> 00:07:42.019
the Posit Public Package Manager, or P3M.

00:07:44.519 --> 00:07:47.760
We also should talk about this field, needs compilation.

00:07:47.760 --> 00:07:50.920
JSON Lite says needs compilation is yes,

00:07:50.920 --> 00:07:53.779
and rrenv says needs compilation is no.

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:57.239
Needs compilation means that this requires

00:07:57.239 --> 00:07:59.980
compiling tools outside of R,

00:07:59.980 --> 00:08:01.959
which touches on your system dependencies

00:08:01.959 --> 00:08:03.380
and your operating system,

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:06.880
which are layers that rrenv does not touch.

00:08:08.359 --> 00:08:11.500
Now we have to talk about binaries.

00:08:11.500 --> 00:08:14.059
So binaries are compiled R packages.

00:08:14.059 --> 00:08:17.339
They are very specific to your operating system,

00:08:17.339 --> 00:08:22.019
your R version, your package version, and architecture.

00:08:22.019 --> 00:08:23.839
Typically, when we install packages,

00:08:23.839 --> 00:08:27.660
we either install them from source or binary.

00:08:27.660 --> 00:08:31.399
If we start from binary, it's a straight shot to install.

00:08:31.399 --> 00:08:34.380
If we start from source, then our machine

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:36.440
has to compile it into a binary,

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:38.400
and then we get to install it.

00:08:38.400 --> 00:08:40.719
So that needs compilation step happens

00:08:40.719 --> 00:08:43.340
in between going from source to binary,

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:45.400
which means when we install from source,

00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:48.080
this is a harder and slower process,

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:50.000
whereas if we install from binary,

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.080
this is an easier and faster process.

00:08:53.080 --> 00:08:56.679
And typically, the reason why we'll do one over the other

00:08:56.679 --> 00:08:59.520
is just simply the availability of the binaries.

00:08:59.520 --> 00:09:00.960
They're not always available.

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:05.479
So now, let's talk about projects over time.

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:10.119
I'm gonna pick up this project six months later,

00:09:10.119 --> 00:09:14.039
in August of this year, and I'm gonna actively work on it.

00:09:14.039 --> 00:09:17.940
And when I pick it up, the entire ecosystem has changed.

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:20.940
There's a new version of R, a new version of rrenv,

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:23.280
and a new version of Jsonlite.

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:25.919
And so now, I have to make some project decisions,

00:09:25.919 --> 00:09:28.460
freeze, manage, or update.

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:30.820
And we're gonna think about this

00:09:30.820 --> 00:09:32.859
in this versions over time map,

00:09:32.859 --> 00:09:36.219
where on one axis, we have our R version increasing,

00:09:36.219 --> 00:09:37.440
and on the other axis,

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:39.859
we have our package version increasing.

00:09:39.859 --> 00:09:42.020
And where we're starting with our initial project

00:09:42.020 --> 00:09:44.619
is right here in the top left-hand corner

00:09:44.619 --> 00:09:48.820
with R 4.4.2 and Jsonlite 1.8.9.

00:09:50.619 --> 00:09:52.260
So let's talk about the freeze option.

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:54.900
What does this mean in the context of rrenv?

00:09:56.299 --> 00:09:58.200
So I'm gonna pose the question

00:09:58.940 --> 00:10:02.200
that I am really excited about the new release of base R,

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:05.640
and I want to advance to R 4.5.1.

00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:06.840
And so can I do this?

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:09.219
Can I advance to R 4.5.1,

00:10:09.219 --> 00:10:12.440
but still use older versions of rrenv and Jsonlite

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:14.340
when I pick up my active project?

00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:18.039
And so if we're thinking about what's happening here,

00:10:18.039 --> 00:10:21.479
we have moved forward in time, R 4.51 is out,

00:10:21.479 --> 00:10:22.919
and I want to use it,

00:10:22.919 --> 00:10:25.080
but I wanna move backwards in time

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:27.919
and use an older version of Jsonlite.

00:10:28.599 --> 00:10:29.440
Can I do this?

00:10:30.200 --> 00:10:32.760
And let's be explicit about what we're doing here.

00:10:32.760 --> 00:10:36.039
If we're using a new R version, we will get a new cache.

00:10:36.039 --> 00:10:38.719
I had everything working just the way I wanted to

00:10:38.719 --> 00:10:42.239
under R 4.4, and now when I'm using R 4.5,

00:10:42.239 --> 00:10:44.520
my cache is empty, so I will be forced

00:10:44.520 --> 00:10:46.039
to install new packages.

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:49.960
And so we're going to open up this project

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:53.479
under R 4.5.1, and we're going to push the only button

00:10:53.479 --> 00:10:57.359
we know how to push, which is rrenv restore.

00:10:57.359 --> 00:11:00.760
And unfortunately, I get my failure message, right?

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:04.119
It says I am attempting to install Jsonlite

00:11:04.119 --> 00:11:07.039
from source, and it failed.

00:11:07.039 --> 00:11:10.520
Instead of crying, let's push our second button.

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:12.280
Evaluate our project state

00:11:12.280 --> 00:11:14.940
against our current, our configuration.

00:11:16.059 --> 00:11:19.320
So my first question is, do I have the configuration

00:11:19.320 --> 00:11:21.960
required for source compilation?

00:11:23.679 --> 00:11:27.000
I'm on Windows 11, I have RTools 4.5,

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:29.320
and the answer is yes, I do.

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:31.119
All the machinery is there.

00:11:32.239 --> 00:11:34.000
And I can programmatically check that

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.760
with a function package build check builds tools,

00:11:36.760 --> 00:11:39.000
which yields the result, your system is ready

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:40.460
to build packages.

00:11:40.460 --> 00:11:42.219
So that's kind of weird.

00:11:43.799 --> 00:11:46.000
Well, if installing from source is a problem,

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:48.400
can I just install from binary instead, right?

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:51.099
I can just bypass this whole compilation issue.

00:11:52.159 --> 00:11:54.080
And that gets a little muddy.

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:58.380
So let's think about when binaries are generally available.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:02.599
When I started this project in February of this year,

00:12:02.599 --> 00:12:05.400
Jsonlite 1.8.9 was the latest and greatest

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:06.919
that was available on CRAN,

00:12:06.919 --> 00:12:08.479
and the binary for this package

00:12:08.479 --> 00:12:10.260
was available on CRAN at that time,

00:12:10.260 --> 00:12:13.280
and also on Posit Public Package Manager P3M.

00:12:13.280 --> 00:12:15.799
And the gray squares were future versions.

00:12:15.799 --> 00:12:19.280
Now, six months later, CRAN hosts binaries

00:12:19.280 --> 00:12:21.880
for latest available package versions.

00:12:21.880 --> 00:12:25.799
So Jsonlite 2.0 is gonna be on CRAN, not 1.8.9.

00:12:27.479 --> 00:12:29.039
If I do wanna go back in time,

00:12:29.039 --> 00:12:33.719
P3M does actually host binaries for older releases.

00:12:33.719 --> 00:12:38.440
But where I'm at in the upper right-hand corner

00:12:38.440 --> 00:12:41.799
of this matrix, there is no binary available

00:12:41.799 --> 00:12:43.880
for this combination of things.

00:12:46.479 --> 00:12:49.280
So can I install from binary instead?

00:12:49.280 --> 00:12:50.500
The answer is no.

00:12:51.340 --> 00:12:54.659
Which leads me to think, am I doing something weird?

00:12:55.580 --> 00:12:58.940
So you get a little hint of this at the top of your console.

00:12:58.940 --> 00:13:02.500
RM tells you, hey, you're using R 4.51,

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:06.299
but your log file was generated with R 4.4.2.

00:13:06.299 --> 00:13:09.900
And that picture we just showed about binary availability

00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:11.940
speaks to a general reflection

00:13:11.940 --> 00:13:15.419
of what's going on in the R ecosystem.

00:13:15.419 --> 00:13:19.820
So in the R ecosystem, things work really well

00:13:19.820 --> 00:13:21.739
at any given point in time when we're looking

00:13:21.739 --> 00:13:25.659
at latest releases available at that point in time.

00:13:25.659 --> 00:13:28.979
The diagonal is a good place to be.

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:34.020
The lower triangle is also an okay place to be.

00:13:34.020 --> 00:13:36.940
We can do things like stay on R 4.4

00:13:36.940 --> 00:13:39.739
and use a newer version of a package.

00:13:39.739 --> 00:13:42.020
The upper triangle, no.

00:13:42.020 --> 00:13:43.979
We don't want to be here.

00:13:43.979 --> 00:13:48.619
This is undefined, uncharted territory.

00:13:48.619 --> 00:13:51.840
And if you find yourself lost and wandering

00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:55.119
to this undefined territory, it's not your fault.

00:13:55.119 --> 00:13:57.659
It's nothing to be ashamed of.

00:13:57.659 --> 00:14:01.020
With RM, unfortunately, it is quite easy

00:14:01.020 --> 00:14:04.859
to accidentally do something that is quite unnatural

00:14:04.859 --> 00:14:06.539
to the R ecosystem.

00:14:07.380 --> 00:14:09.260
But if you do find yourself there,

00:14:09.260 --> 00:14:11.460
I want you to look at yourself in the mirror,

00:14:11.460 --> 00:14:14.820
say no, and slap yourself out of it.

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:17.659
I'm not saying things won't ever work there.

00:14:17.659 --> 00:14:19.340
They will work sometimes.

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:23.580
But eventually, you will hit unnecessary pain and suffering.

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:27.299
So am I doing something weird?

00:14:27.299 --> 00:14:28.239
Yes.

00:14:30.179 --> 00:14:33.539
So the correct way to freeze a project

00:14:33.539 --> 00:14:36.059
is to return to its initial state.

00:14:36.059 --> 00:14:39.559
I want to revert back to that original R version.

00:14:41.099 --> 00:14:42.659
So let's go back in time.

00:14:42.659 --> 00:14:46.219
Now, if you're not aware, you can have multiple versions

00:14:46.219 --> 00:14:47.979
of R installed on your machine,

00:14:47.979 --> 00:14:50.099
and a wonderful tool for switching

00:14:50.099 --> 00:14:52.419
between those R versions is called rig,

00:14:52.419 --> 00:14:55.619
which is known as the R installation manager.

00:14:55.619 --> 00:15:00.619
So in your terminal, you can submit rig default 4.4.2.

00:15:00.619 --> 00:15:04.179
So now, I've reverted back to my original version of R,

00:15:04.179 --> 00:15:07.299
and at this point, RM restore becomes a trivial

00:15:07.299 --> 00:15:08.960
and easy process.

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:12.340
So I can successfully install package versions

00:15:12.340 --> 00:15:14.659
from my repository specified in the lock file.

00:15:14.659 --> 00:15:17.739
And remember, that was originally set to CRAN

00:15:17.739 --> 00:15:19.700
when I started this six months ago.

00:15:19.700 --> 00:15:22.340
Now, I've advanced in the future,

00:15:22.340 --> 00:15:25.179
and when I'm looking at my binary availability chart,

00:15:25.179 --> 00:15:27.380
if I'm really trying to go back in time

00:15:27.380 --> 00:15:30.460
to this version 1.8.9,

00:15:30.460 --> 00:15:34.380
that's no longer available on CRAN in binary.

00:15:34.380 --> 00:15:37.260
So if I want to take advantage of that binary,

00:15:37.260 --> 00:15:40.580
I can go to P3M to get that binary.

00:15:40.580 --> 00:15:43.460
And you can do that by supplying the repose argument

00:15:43.460 --> 00:15:45.859
in the RM restore function.

00:15:45.859 --> 00:15:48.440
And there's a third way you can do this,

00:15:48.440 --> 00:15:51.960
which is with the RM checkout function.

00:15:51.960 --> 00:15:55.219
So in RM checkout, you supply a date,

00:15:55.219 --> 00:15:58.500
and then RM will install date-based package versions

00:15:58.500 --> 00:16:01.299
such that they fetch the latest available versions

00:16:01.299 --> 00:16:02.380
up to that date.

00:16:05.020 --> 00:16:07.099
Let's talk about the manage decision.

00:16:08.340 --> 00:16:10.900
So I'm calling it manage when I want to maintain

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:13.619
my R version of 4.4.2,

00:16:13.619 --> 00:16:17.380
but I want to advance to JSON Lite 2.0

00:16:17.380 --> 00:16:18.940
to use the latest and greatest.

00:16:20.500 --> 00:16:22.960
And remember, this is an okay place to be

00:16:22.960 --> 00:16:24.380
in the R ecosystem.

00:16:26.299 --> 00:16:27.500
This is pretty simple.

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:30.299
In this case, I would do install of JSON Lite,

00:16:30.299 --> 00:16:33.140
and then snapshot to record that to my lock file.

00:16:34.979 --> 00:16:37.020
And lastly, what about update?

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:40.260
Update means I want to bring everything forward

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:43.500
into the future, including my R and my package versions.

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:47.219
And in our R ecosystem map, this is a great place to be.

00:16:48.179 --> 00:16:49.780
There's three steps to updating.

00:16:49.780 --> 00:16:52.500
First, you'll execute RM upgrade

00:16:52.500 --> 00:16:55.679
to upgrade RM to the latest available version.

00:16:55.679 --> 00:16:57.500
Then you'll execute RM install

00:16:57.500 --> 00:16:59.479
to install all latest package versions.

00:16:59.479 --> 00:17:02.099
And lastly, snapshot to record those versions

00:17:02.099 --> 00:17:03.059
to the lock file.

00:17:04.699 --> 00:17:05.660
And I want to be clear here

00:17:05.660 --> 00:17:08.300
that if you're actively working on a project,

00:17:08.339 --> 00:17:11.979
regularly updating is the happy path.

00:17:11.979 --> 00:17:14.500
It allows you to reckon with upgrading

00:17:14.500 --> 00:17:17.420
your package versions in a controlled manner.

00:17:19.780 --> 00:17:21.280
So to summarize,

00:17:24.099 --> 00:17:28.640
RM places an immense amount of responsibility on the user.

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:30.900
And it is a package that you should truly

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:34.260
read the documentation front to end.

00:17:34.260 --> 00:17:35.699
Because what we've talked about here

00:17:35.699 --> 00:17:38.439
in terms of what RM does and does not do for you

00:17:38.439 --> 00:17:40.939
is listed in the caveats.

00:17:40.939 --> 00:17:42.920
So please, read the documentation.

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:47.400
And another framework that's in the RM documentation

00:17:47.400 --> 00:17:50.180
is how you handle active projects.

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:53.020
It gives you these kind of decision-making frameworks.

00:17:53.020 --> 00:17:56.260
And if you're using RM on an active project,

00:17:56.260 --> 00:17:57.939
if you're thinking about the freeze option,

00:17:57.939 --> 00:18:01.260
I just want to keep those package versions stable,

00:18:01.260 --> 00:18:03.140
that's really just short-term sustainable.

00:18:03.140 --> 00:18:04.380
It's gonna come back to bite you,

00:18:04.380 --> 00:18:07.579
and it's gonna be harder the more time that elapses.

00:18:07.579 --> 00:18:10.439
Managing by doing one-off upgrades of a package

00:18:10.439 --> 00:18:12.079
is also short-term sustainable.

00:18:12.079 --> 00:18:15.439
It's gonna really kind of lead to a fragile R ecosystem.

00:18:16.479 --> 00:18:18.079
And then updating is truly

00:18:18.079 --> 00:18:20.479
the only long-term sustainable way to go.

00:18:22.060 --> 00:18:24.560
And if you think about the reproducibility spectrum,

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:28.040
just remember where RM sits, right in the middle.

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:30.959
There might be times and places where you need to go

00:18:30.959 --> 00:18:33.479
to the upper end of that reproducibility spectrum

00:18:33.479 --> 00:18:36.540
and use something like a container, like Docker.

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:38.579
And I love this example from Andrew Heiss.

00:18:38.579 --> 00:18:41.000
He's got a wonderful repository

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:44.560
that shows you how you can execute code

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:47.859
from a published paper using all methods of the spectrum,

00:18:47.859 --> 00:18:50.000
using Docker, using renv,

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.920
or just using packages installed locally system-wide.

00:18:54.780 --> 00:18:56.380
So to go back to what David said,

00:18:56.380 --> 00:18:58.819
you should use renv, I agree,

00:18:58.819 --> 00:19:00.739
but you should use it with intention.

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:05.479
There's a lot of places you can get into the weeds here.

00:19:05.479 --> 00:19:06.979
I didn't have time for everything.

00:19:06.979 --> 00:19:08.719
So if you want more tips and details,

00:19:08.719 --> 00:19:10.319
you can go to my GitHub repository,

00:19:10.319 --> 00:19:12.800
Shannon Pileggi, PracticalRenv.

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:15.119
And I wanna give you a huge thank you to David

00:19:15.119 --> 00:19:16.880
for helping me reason through all of this,

00:19:16.880 --> 00:19:19.040
and Kevin for also listening to this,

00:19:19.040 --> 00:19:22.280
and everyone else who's supported me along the way.

00:19:22.579 --> 00:19:23.660
Thank you.

00:19:23.660 --> 00:19:25.760
Thank you.

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:26.819
Thank you.

00:19:26.819 --> 00:19:28.199
Thank you.

00:19:28.199 --> 00:19:29.719
Thank you.

00:19:29.719 --> 00:19:30.540
Thank you.

00:19:31.500 --> 00:19:33.040
Thank you.

00:19:37.839 --> 00:19:38.839
Thank you.

